<TITLE> Hasina talks climate change with Danish minister </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 4 (bdnews24.com)The government plans to ensure flow and navigability of major rivers with a view to combating effects of climate change and boosting farm production. Prime minister Sheikh Hasina spoke of the plan among other strategies to combat climate change during talks with visiting Danish climate and energy minister Connie Hedegaard on Wednesday, the PM's press secretary Abul Kalam Azad told reporters. "Sheikh Hasina and the Danish minister discussed climate change and energy related issues. They also talked about enhancing trade and commerce between the two countries," said Azad. The Awami League government is committed to creating a poverty-free and prosperous nation by 2021, the golden jubilee of Bangladesh's independence, the PM told the visitor. "Replying to a query posed by Hedegaard, the prime minister said the ordinances promulgated during the caretaker government's rule will be disposed of according to the recommendations of the special parliamentary committee set up in this regard," said Azad. "The special committee, comprising members from the opposition too, will consult experts and resolve the issue within 30 days, Sheikh Hasina told the minister," said the press secretary. Denmark will provide all possible assistance in Bangladesh's fight against climate change, the Danish minister assured Hasina. Kazi Aminul Islam, secretary to the PMO and Danish ambassador Einar H Jensen were also present during the meeting. bdnews2
